        $trends = [
            [
                'title'   => 'GPT-4 Launches and Sets a New Frontier for AI Reasoning',
                'summary' => 'OpenAI\'s GPT-4 demonstrates human-level performance on professional and academic benchmarks — scoring in the 90th percentile on the bar exam and surpassing GPT-3.5 on virtually every evaluated task — establishing a new standard for large language model capability.',
                'content' => "GPT-4, released by OpenAI in March 2023, represented the most significant leap in large language model capability since the original GPT-3 in 2020. Unlike its predecessor, GPT-4 is a multimodal model accepting both text and image inputs, and its performance on structured professional assessments was striking: 90th percentile on the Uniform Bar Examination, 99th percentile on the Biology Olympiad, top 10% on the SAT, and passing scores on the USMLE medical licensing examination. These results transformed the public and scientific discourse about AI capability from theoretical potential to demonstrated near-term impact on knowledge professions.\n\nThe qualitative improvements in GPT-4 over GPT-3.5 were as significant as the benchmark scores. The model exhibited substantially improved calibration — more accurately expressing uncertainty rather than confidently asserting incorrect information. Its instruction following was more precise and reliable, reducing the rate of misinterpretation of complex or multi-part requests. Its reasoning on logical and mathematical problems improved dramatically, particularly on multi-step problems where prior models would drift or make arithmetic errors mid-chain. The overall impression to users was a model that could be trusted with more consequential tasks.\n\nOpenAI's technical report for GPT-4 was unusually sparse on architectural and training details, citing competitive concerns — a departure from the company's earlier tradition of detailed research publications. The report confirmed the model was a transformer but withheld parameter count, training data composition, and training compute. This opacity generated controversy in the research community and marked a turning point in OpenAI's relationship with the open-science ethos it had originally embodied. The competitive dynamics of AI development were now operating at a scale where technical transparency was viewed as a strategic liability.\n\nThe integration of GPT-4 into Microsoft's Bing search engine and into the ChatGPT Plus subscription launched the first mass-market deployment of frontier AI in consumer products. Bing's GPT-4-powered chat mode attracted 100 million daily active users within weeks. Microsoft's simultaneous integration of GPT-4 capabilities across Office applications under the Copilot brand — drafting Word documents, generating Excel formulas, summarizing Teams meetings, composing Outlook emails — began the transition of enterprise productivity software toward AI-native workflows that would accelerate throughout the year.",
                'status'  => 'published',
                'year'    => 2023,
            ],
            [
                'title'   => 'ChatGPT Reaches 100 Million Users, Triggering the Generative AI Gold Rush',
                'summary' => 'ChatGPT becomes the fastest consumer product in history to reach 100 million users, catalyzing over $40 billion in generative AI investment in 2023 and forcing every major technology company to accelerate its AI strategy.',
                'content' => "ChatGPT's launch in November 2022 and its sustained viral growth through early 2023 produced the most dramatic consumer technology adoption curve in recorded history. The service reached 100 million monthly active users in January 2023 — just two months after launch — surpassing the growth rates of Instagram (2.5 years), TikTok (9 months), and every prior consumer internet product. By mid-2023, ChatGPT was receiving over 1.8 billion monthly visits, making it among the most visited websites globally despite being less than a year old.\n\nThe market response to ChatGPT's success was immediate and massive. Venture capital investment in generative AI companies reached approximately $40 billion in 2023, with Anthropic raising $7.3 billion, Inflection AI raising $1.3 billion, Cohere raising $270 million, Mistral AI raising $113 million at a $260 million valuation within months of founding, and dozens of application-layer companies attracting significant funding to build on top of foundation model APIs. The term \"generative AI\" entered mainstream business vocabulary, appearing in earnings calls, board presentations, and strategic plans across virtually every industry sector.\n\nThe incumbent technology companies were caught in various states of preparation. Google, whose researchers had invented the transformer architecture underlying GPT-4 and published the original \"Attention Is All You Need\" paper, was criticized for a slow response that reflected its careful, committee-driven approach to deploying AI in consumer products. Its hastily launched Bard chatbot produced an error in its demonstration video, wiping $100 billion from Alphabet's market cap in a single day — a cautionary tale about the pressure AI competition was now creating on product launch decisions. Meta, Microsoft, and Amazon each accelerated their own generative AI product timelines significantly.\n\nThe cultural impact of ChatGPT extended far beyond the technology industry. Academic integrity policies were rewritten at universities globally within months. The Writers Guild of America's 2023 strike included AI protections as a central demand. Major news organizations ran front-page stories about AI's implications for employment. Polling showed that public awareness of AI rose from minority to majority awareness in developed countries within a single year. Few technologies in history have moved so rapidly from specialist tool to cultural phenomenon.",
                'status'  => 'published',
                'year'    => 2023,
